    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-07-27T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-07-27T09:00:00-05:00" n="94"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d94">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.5/7–2750: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The United States Deputy Representative on the North Atlantic
                        Council</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Spofford</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-07-27T15:00:00+01:00"
                            >July 27, 1950—3 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Depto1">Depto</gloss> 13. From Spofford. Eyes only Secretaries
                    of State, Defense and General Bradley. Following is substance of “private”
                    handwritten letter from Montgomery received this morning (<gloss
                        target="#t_Depto1">Depto</gloss> 7).</p>
                <p>Shinwell believes basis of problem is equipment. Montgomery disagrees and
                    considers organization prerequisite to adequate utilization of equipment. In his
                    view organization falls under three heads: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>The nations concerned must create organization capable of bringing
                            about effective joint defense in Europe. Such an organization has never
                            yet been established.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Within each nation there must be system capable of producing military
                            quota of that nation in accordance with requirements. No nation in
                            continental Europe has such system. </item>
                        <pb facs="0167" n="145" xml:id="pg_145"/>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>There must be setup for command and control able to take charge
                            quickly when emergency begins to develop. This setup must be established
                            now in peace time.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Once properly organized West could begin to develop effective defense; without it
                    we will merely drift as in past two years.</p>
                <closer>[<signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Spofford</hi>
                    </signed>]</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
